Recommendations:
1.31	We recommended that the Local Chief Executive direct the City Accounting Office (CACCO), the City General Services Office (CGSO), and the Information and Communications Technology (ICT) unit to:
1.31.1	conduct a joint reconciliation of the ₱29,560,803.18 inventory accounts by verifying the ₱1,164,849.34 discrepancies between the accounting records and the Report on the Physical Count of Inventories (RPCI) within 60 days, including the correction of the ₱2,558,357.92 and ₱113,569.70 variances in Materials and Drugs and Medicines Inventory, respectively;
1.31.2	implement strict monitoring controls by ensuring that all inventory receipts and issuances are recorded based on the charge invoice date and Acceptance and Inspection Report (AIR) completion date, not on supplier payment date, effective immediately;
1.31.3	enforce the weekly consolidation and timely submission of the Summary of Supplies and Materials Issued (SSMI) by CGSO to CACCO; and
1.31.4	integrate the e-PROCS inventory system with the ECPAC accounting system within 12 months to automate data sharing, enhance accuracy, and reduce reconciliation time.

Recommendations:
2.9	We recommended that Management:
2.9.1	immediately discontinue the practice of recording procured inventory items/goods as outright expenses and ensure that all purchases are recognized as assets under the appropriate inventory accounts in accordance with Sections 120, 121, and 126 of Volume I of the NGAS Manual for LGUs;
2.9.2	direct the City Accounting Office (CACCO), within 60 days from receipt of this recommendation, to develop and enforce standardized procedures for recording and monitoring inventory transactions, ensuring compliance with the NGAS Manual and mandating monthly reconciliation between procurement records and inventory accounts to prevent future misstatements;
2.9.3	direct CACCO and the City General Services Office (CGSO), within 90 days from receipt of this recommendation, conduct a joint reconciliation of all inventory purchases for the current fiscal year to identify misclassified expenses, ensure necessary adjustments to the inventory and expense accounts, and verify the accuracy of the financial statements, with the reconciliation report submitted to the Audit Team upon completion; and
2.9.4	 establish a systematic process to track and account for all inventory items by assigning responsibility to designated personnel for safeguarding inventory and ensuring all movements are documented through the Supplies Ledger Cards (SLC) and the Report on the Physical Count of Inventories (RPCI) within 120 days from receipt of this recommendation.

We recommended and Management agreed to:
instruct the CAO to provide a list of all unissued Inventories to the CGSO as of December 31, 2024 in order to facilitate the preparation and/or tracing of supporting documents necessary for the recording of its issuances;
require the CGSO to submit the RIS, SSMI, Distribution Lists and/or WMR to CAO on or before August 31, 2025 in order to adjust all unissued Inventories as of December 31, 2024;
assign additional Job Order or Contract of Service Personnel in the CGSO who will assist in the conduct of semi-annual physical count of Inventories, preparation of the RPCI and reconciliation of the RPCI with the ending balance of Inventories as of cut-off date;
immediately enforce stricter inventory controls by requiring the CGSO and the Inventory Committee to conduct semi-annual physical inventory counts with the assistance of supplies custodians from all offices. Additionally, the CGSO, Inventory Committee, and CAO must promptly reconcile inventory records to ensure accurate balances. The RPCI should be submitted to the Office of the Auditor not later than July 31 and January 31 of each year for the first and second semesters, respectively; and
direct the CAO to record adjusting entries after completing the reconciliation with the CGSO. This ensures that only the accurate remaining balances of inventory items are reflected in the books of accounts, improving the reliability of financial records.

Recommendations:
We recommend and the Management agreed to adopt the following measures as provided in the COA Circular 2020-006:
Reinforce the Inventory Committee which shall be composed of an adequate number of members to be able to complete the physical inventory in three months or less;
Ensure that the members of the Inventory Committee shall be temporarily relieved of all their regular duties to devote their full time in the conduct of the physical inventory taking until the same is completed;
Ensure that the Inventory Committee shall be responsible for the actual count to ascertain the existence, completeness and condition of all PPEs owned by the Province;
In coordination with the Property Division/Unit, the Inventory Committee shall plan/strategize on how to conduct and complete the physical inventory within the prescribed period. It shall prepare a Physical Inventory Plan (PIP) containing, at the least, the specific assignments/duties of the Committee members, the cut-off date, and a schedule specifying the dates and locations of the inventory taking activities from start-up to the targeted completion of the physical inventory; and
Property records shall be updated based on the results of the physical inventory and reconciled with accounting records to come up with the reconciled balances of PPE accounts to be considered as the correct balance of the agency's PPE.

